					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/smapti" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(362048); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=362048&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610183099" alt="Smapti" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=362048)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/smapti" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(362048); return false;" >Smapti</a></span> <span class="odate time_1350851386 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">21 Oct 2012 20:29</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1593856">
									

<p>Strange.</p>
<p>It's hard for me to imagine Lord Blackwood as a tired old man, let alone one standing witnesses to World War I. He's such a product of the Victorian era - an era where Britain stood undefeated on the global stage and the advance of science heralded a new age of enlightenment. For him to then see all of those progresses turned into industrialized mass murder that decimated an entire generation and left its survivors as world-weary cynics&#8230; how could he bear it?</p>
<p>On the other hand, maybe <em>that's</em> why he's since chosen to ignore the last century, and believe that Victoria is still the queen, Edison's motion-picture-camera is the latest in scientific innovation, and Britannia still rules the waves.</p>
<p>I'll have to think about this one before I decide how to vote on it.</p>

							</div>

								
					
