					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/smapti" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(362048); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=362048&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610183099" alt="Smapti" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=362048)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/smapti" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(362048); return false;" >Smapti</a></span> <span class="odate time_1350854638 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">21 Oct 2012 21:23</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1593905">
									

<p>I don't think i've ever described Lord Blackwood as &quot;incapable of fault&quot;. By any standard, his worldview is parochial and chauvinist, his attitudes towards women and minorities are reprehensible, and he rushes headlong into danger without considering the consequences. I've only written one tale where he nets a clean &quot;victory&quot; at the end - most of the time, he barely makes it out alive, and there's nobody around to confirm his tales anyway.</p>
<p>It's just&#8230; I have trouble imagining him outside his temporal &quot;comfort zone&quot;, that's all.</p>

							</div>

								
					
